=========================================================
COPY CONSTRUCTOR & COPY ASSIGNMENT OPERATOR
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================================

=========================================================
1. COPY CONSTRUCTOR
=========================================================

Definition:
Creates a new object from an existing object.

Syntax:

ClassName(const ClassName& other);

Example:

MyClass a;
MyClass b = a;      // Copy Constructor

OR

MyClass b(a);       // Copy Constructor

When is it called?

1. Object initialization

   MyClass b = a;

2. Pass by value

   void fun(MyClass obj);

3. Return by value
   (if copy elision doesn't occur)

=========================================================
2. COPY ASSIGNMENT OPERATOR
=========================================================

Definition:
Copies data into an already existing object.

Syntax:

ClassName& operator=(const ClassName& other);

Example:

MyClass a;
MyClass b;

b = a;              // Copy Assignment Operator

When is it called?

When assigning one existing object to another.

=========================================================
3. COPY CONSTRUCTOR vs COPY ASSIGNMENT
=========================================================

Example:

MyClass a;

MyClass b = a;   // Copy Constructor

MyClass c;
c = a;           // Copy Assignment Operator

Key Difference:

Copy Constructor:
Creates a NEW object.

Copy Assignment:
Assigns to an EXISTING object.

=========================================================
4. DEFAULT COPY BEHAVIOR
=========================================================

Compiler-generated copy constructor and assignment
perform SHALLOW COPY.

Example:

class Test
{
    int* ptr;
};

Default copy:

obj2.ptr = obj1.ptr;

Both objects point to the same memory.

Problem:

obj1 ---> Memory <--- obj2

When destructors run:

delete ptr;
delete ptr;

Result:
Double Deletion (Undefined Behavior)

=========================================================
5. DEEP COPY
=========================================================

Allocate new memory and copy actual data.

Example:

Test(const Test& other)
{
    ptr = new int(*other.ptr);
}

Now each object owns separate memory.

=========================================================
6. COPY ASSIGNMENT OPERATOR (DEEP COPY)
=========================================================

Test& operator=(const Test& other)
{
    if(this != &other)
    {
        delete ptr;

        ptr = new int(*other.ptr);
    }

    return *this;
}

=========================================================
7. WHY SELF-ASSIGNMENT CHECK?
=========================================================

Without check:

obj = obj;

delete ptr;

Now ptr is deleted.

Trying to copy from same object causes problems.

Solution:

if(this != &other)

=========================================================
8. RULE OF THREE
=========================================================

If a class defines any one of:

1. Destructor
2. Copy Constructor
3. Copy Assignment Operator

It usually needs all three.

Reason:
Class manages a resource.

=========================================================
9. RULE OF FIVE (C++11)
=========================================================

1. Destructor
2. Copy Constructor
3. Copy Assignment Operator
4. Move Constructor
5. Move Assignment Operator

=========================================================
10. WHY unique_ptr DELETES COPY OPERATIONS?
=========================================================

std::unique_ptr provides exclusive ownership.

Two unique_ptr objects cannot own the same resource.

Therefore:

unique_ptr(const unique_ptr&) = delete;

unique_ptr& operator=(const unique_ptr&) = delete;

=========================================================
11. WHY unique_ptr ALLOWS MOVE?
=========================================================

Move transfers ownership.

Example:

unique_ptr<int> p1(new int(10));

unique_ptr<int> p2(std::move(p1));

After move:

p1 --> nullptr
p2 --> owns resource

=========================================================
12. MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a Copy Constructor?

A:
A constructor that creates a new object from an
existing object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. What is a Copy Assignment Operator?

A:
An operator that copies data from one object into
another already existing object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Difference between Copy Constructor and
Copy Assignment Operator?

A:

Copy Constructor:
Creates a new object.

Copy Assignment:
Assigns to an existing object.

Example:

MyClass b = a;   // Copy Constructor

MyClass c;
c = a;           // Copy Assignment

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. When is Copy Constructor called?

A:

1. Object initialization
2. Pass by value
3. Return by value (if copy elision not applied)

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Why is self-assignment check needed?

A:

To safely handle:

obj = obj;

and avoid deleting the resource before copying it.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. What is shallow copy?

A:

Copying pointer values only.

Both objects point to the same memory.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. What is deep copy?

A:

Allocating new memory and copying actual data.

Each object owns separate memory.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. What problem does shallow copy cause?

A:

Double deletion and undefined behavior.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. What is Rule of Three?

A:

If a class defines Destructor, Copy Constructor,
or Copy Assignment Operator, it usually needs all three.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. What is Rule of Five?

A:

Destructor
Copy Constructor
Copy Assignment
Move Constructor
Move Assignment

---------------------------------------------------------

Q11. Why is Copy Constructor parameter passed as
const reference?

A:

Passing by value would invoke the copy constructor
again, causing infinite recursion.

Correct:

MyClass(const MyClass& other);

=========================================================
ONE-LINE INTERVIEW ANSWERS
=========================================================

Copy Constructor:
Creates a new object from an existing object.

Copy Assignment:
Copies data into an already existing object.

Shallow Copy:
Copies pointer addresses only.

Deep Copy:
Allocates new memory and copies actual data.

Rule of Three:
Destructor + Copy Constructor + Copy Assignment.

Rule of Five:
Rule of Three + Move Constructor + Move Assignment.

Self-Assignment Check:
Prevents problems when an object is assigned to itself.

unique_ptr Copy:
Deleted because ownership must be unique.

unique_ptr Move:
Allowed because ownership can be transferred.
